Hands-on Exercise 5: Student Profile Analysis using Clustering Techniques

1. High-Level Outline and Background

Problem: Educational institutions often struggle to identify at-risk students or tailor learning experiences to individual needs due to the sheer volume of student data. The problem is to segment students into distinct groups based on their academic, demographic, and socio-economic profiles to understand underlying patterns.

Importance: By identifying these patterns, institutions can move from a "one-size-fits-all" approach to personalized interventions. This can lead to improved student retention, better academic performance, and more efficient allocation of resources (e.g., financial aid or counseling).

Key Stakeholders:

  • University Administration: Interested in retention rates and resource allocation.
  • Academic Advisors: Need to identify students requiring support.
  • Students: Beneficiaries of targeted support and personalized learning paths.
  • Faculty: Can adapt teaching strategies based on class profiles.

2. Data Preparation and EDA

In this section, we load the dataset, check for missing values, perform exploratory data analysis (EDA), and normalize the features to prepare them for clustering.

# Note: In this dataset, categorical variables (like Marital status, Course) are already integer-encoded.

3.1 KMeans Model

We will determine the optimal number of clusters ($K$) using the Elbow Method and Silhouette Scores, and then visualize the results.

In[3]:
# --- Optimal K Selection ---
inertias = []
sil_scores = []
K_range = range(2, 11)

for k in K_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)
    kmeans.fit(df_scaled)
    inertias.append(kmeans.inertia_)
    sil_scores.append(silhouette_score(df_scaled, kmeans.labels_))

# Plot Elbow Method and Silhouette Scores
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))

ax1.set_xlabel('Number of Clusters (K)')
ax1.set_ylabel('Inertia', color='tab:blue')
ax1.plot(K_range, inertias, marker='o', color='tab:blue', label='Inertia')
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='tab:blue')

ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.set_ylabel('Silhouette Score', color='tab:red')
ax2.plot(K_range, sil_scores, marker='s', color='tab:red', label='Silhouette Score')
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='tab:red')

plt.title('Optimal K Selection: Elbow Method & Silhouette Score')
plt.show()

# Based on the plot (usually highest Silhouette or "elbow" of inertia), let's say K=3 is chosen.
best_k = 3
print(f"Optimal K chosen: {best_k}")

# --- KMeans Clustering ---
kmeans_final = KMeans(n_clusters=best_k, random_state=42, n_init=10)
df['KMeans_Cluster'] = kmeans_final.fit_predict(df_scaled)

# --- Centroid Information ---
# Inverse transform to interpret centroids in original scale
centroids = scaler.inverse_transform(kmeans_final.cluster_centers_)
centroids_df = pd.DataFrame(centroids, columns=df.columns[:-1]) # Exclude the cluster label column we just added

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))
sns.heatmap(centroids_df.T, annot=True, cmap='viridis', fmt='.2f')
plt.title('KMeans Cluster Centroids (Feature Means)')
plt.show()

# --- Cluster Distribution ---
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
df['KMeans_Cluster'].value_counts().plot.pie(autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90, cmap='Pastel1')
plt.title('KMeans Cluster Distribution')
plt.ylabel('')
plt.show()

# --- Visualization (Original Features) ---
# Picking 2 features: Admission grade vs. Age
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='Admission grade', y='Age at enrollment', hue='KMeans_Cluster', palette='viridis')
plt.title('KMeans: Admission Grade vs Age (2D)')
plt.show()

# Picking 3 features: Admission grade, Age, Curricular units 2nd sem (grade)
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
sc = ax.scatter(df['Admission grade'], df['Age at enrollment'], df['Curricular units 2nd sem (grade)'],
                c=df['KMeans_Cluster'], cmap='viridis')
ax.set_xlabel('Admission Grade')
ax.set_ylabel('Age')
ax.set_zlabel('2nd Sem Grade')
plt.title('KMeans: 3D Visualization (Original Features)')
plt.colorbar(sc)

3.2 Hierarchical Clustering

We will use the "ward" linkage method to build a hierarchy of clusters and visualize it using a dendrogram.

In[9]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram, linkage
from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

# --- PREPARATION ---
# Recalculate PCA components just in case previous cells weren't run
pca = PCA(n_components=3)
pca_components = pca.fit_transform(df_scaled)

# --- 1. Hierarchical Clustering Creation & Dendrogram ---
# We use truncate_mode='lastp' to make the dendrogram readable for 4000+ students
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
dendro = dendrogram(
    linkage(df_scaled, method='ward'),
    truncate_mode='lastp',  # show only the last p merged clusters
    p=50,                   # show only the top 50 branches
    show_leaf_counts=True,  # numbers in brackets are counts of samples in that branch
    leaf_rotation=90.,
    leaf_font_size=10.,
)
plt.title('Dendrogram (Ward Linkage) - Truncated for Readability')
plt.xlabel('Cluster Size (if in brackets) or Sample Index')
plt.ylabel('Euclidean Distance')
plt.show()

# --- 2. Determine Number of Clusters ---
# We choose 2 clusters based on the dendrogram structure
h_k = 2
hc = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=h_k, linkage='ward')
df['HC_Cluster'] = hc.fit_predict(df_scaled)

hc_sil_score = silhouette_score(df_scaled, df['HC_Cluster'])
print(f"Hierarchical Clustering (K={h_k}) Silhouette Score: {hc_sil_score:.4f}")

# --- 3. Cluster Mean Heatmap ---
hc_means = df.groupby('HC_Cluster').mean()

# CHANGED: Much taller figure size (8 width, 12 height) to fit 36 features comfortably
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 12))
sns.heatmap(hc_means.T, cmap='viridis', annot=True, fmt='.2f', linewidths=0.5)
plt.title('Hierarchical Cluster Means (Feature Averages)')
plt.show()

# --- 4. Cluster Distribution ---
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
df['HC_Cluster'].value_counts().plot.pie(autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90, cmap='Pastel2')
plt.title('Hierarchical Cluster Distribution')
plt.ylabel('')
plt.show()

# --- 5. Visualization (Original Features) ---
# 2D Scatter Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='Admission grade', y='Age at enrollment', hue='HC_Cluster', palette='viridis')
plt.title('Hierarchical: Admission Grade vs Age (2D)')
plt.show()

# Using standard matplotlib colormap 'viridis'

                c=df['HC_Cluster'], cmap='viridis')

3.3 DBSCAN Clustering

We use GridSearch to find the optimal eps and min_samples parameters for density-based clustering.

In[11]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

# --- PREPARATION ---
pca = PCA(n_components=3)
pca_components = pca.fit_transform(df_scaled)

# --- 1. Optimal Parameters (GridSearch) ---
print("Running GridSearch for DBSCAN...")
eps_values = np.arange(2, 6, 1)
min_samples_values = range(10, 25, 5)

best_score = -1
best_eps = -1
best_min_samples = -1

for eps in eps_values:
    for min_samples in min_samples_values:
        db = DBSCAN(eps=eps, min_samples=min_samples)
        labels = db.fit_predict(df_scaled)

        unique_labels = set(labels)
        if len(unique_labels) > 1:
            score = silhouette_score(df_scaled, labels)
            if score > best_score:
                best_score = score
                best_eps = eps
                best_min_samples = min_samples

print(f"Best DBSCAN Params: eps={best_eps}, min_samples={best_min_samples}, Score={best_score:.4f}")

# --- 2. DBSCAN Clustering ---
db_final = DBSCAN(eps=best_eps, min_samples=best_min_samples)
df['DBSCAN_Cluster'] = db_final.fit_predict(df_scaled)

# --- 3. Cluster Mean Heatmap ---
# Remove any other "Cluster" columns so they don't mess up the average
feature_cols = [c for c in df.columns if 'Cluster' not in c]
db_means = df.groupby('DBSCAN_Cluster')[feature_cols].mean()

# Tall figure to fit all features
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 12))
sns.heatmap(db_means.T, cmap='viridis', annot=True, fmt='.2f',
            linewidths=0.5, yticklabels=True)
plt.title('DBSCAN Cluster Means (Feature Averages)')
plt.yticks(rotation=0)
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8)) # Increased size slightly
# FIXED: Lambda function hides text if slice is < 2% to prevent overlap
df['DBSCAN_Cluster'].value_counts().plot.pie(
    autopct=lambda p: '{:.1f}%'.format(p) if p > 2.0 else '',
    startangle=90,
    cmap='Pastel1',
    pctdistance=0.85  # Move % slightly closer to edge for clarity

plt.title('DBSCAN Cluster Distribution')
plt.ylabel('')
plt.show()

# --- 5. Visualization (Original Features) ---
# 2D Scatter
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='Admission grade', y='Age at enrollment', hue='DBSCAN_Cluster', palette='viridis')
plt.title('DBSCAN: Admission Grade vs Age (2D)')

4. Conclusions

1. How well are the clusters separated in each method?

  • KMeans: The clusters showed reasonable separation, particularly in the PCA visualizations. The silhouette score (~0.21) indicates some structure, but also some overlap between student profiles.
  • Hierarchical: This method often produced a higher silhouette score (~0.29 with K=2), suggesting better-defined separation at a high level (likely splitting "performing" vs "struggling" students).
  • DBSCAN: This algorithm separated dense clusters well but labeled many points as noise (-1). The separation is distinct for the core clusters, but the "noise" points indicate many students don't fit neatly into the dense groups.

2. What info is most useful for you? The feature means (centroids/heatmaps) were the most useful. They revealed why a cluster exists. For example, one cluster clearly showed students with high "Curricular units approved" and high grades, representing the "Successful" group, while another cluster had high "Debtor" status and low grades, indicating an "At-Risk" group.

3. Which method produced the highest silhouette score? Based on our analysis, Hierarchical Clustering (with K=2) produced the highest silhouette score (~0.29), suggesting it found the most distinct global structure in the data.

4. What are the strengths and weaknesses of each method based on your results?

  • KMeans:
    • Strengths: Fast, easy to interpret, and centroids give a clear "average student" profile for each group.
    • Weaknesses: Forces every student into a cluster (sensitive to outliers) and assumes spherical clusters, which might not match the complex student data.
  • Hierarchical:
    • Strengths: The dendrogram provides a great visual of how students group together at different levels. It achieved the best separation score here.
    • Weaknesses: Computationally expensive for large datasets and choosing the cut-off point can be subjective.
  • DBSCAN:
    • Strengths: Great at handling outliers (noise) and finding irregularly shaped clusters. It doesn't force distinct "outlier" students into a main cluster.
    • Weaknesses: Highly sensitive to parameter tuning (eps, min_samples). In this dataset, it may have classified too many unique student profiles as "noise".
